Googling "vhdl fpga" on Google gave me the following link as the first result:<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://members.optushome.com.au/jekent/FPGA.htm">http://members.optushome.com.au/jekent/FPGA.htm</a><!-- m --><br /><br />And there is no doubt lots of other introductory material out there about fpga development in general.<br /><br />For the powerpak specifically, I guess the only official info is bunnyboy's CNROM example at <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.nespowerpak.com/powerpakdev1.zip">http://www.nespowerpak.com/powerpakdev1.zip</a><!-- m --> , which uses schematics rather than vhdl. Though you could try asking loopy or kyuusaku nicely to share any of their mapper implementations publically.<br /><br />On a practical note, a digital oscilloscope/logic analyzer and some appropriate wires from the cart edge would be extremely helpful when developing. But these things are also very expensive unless you find a really good price on a used one, so it's a luxury you might have to do without. (no, I don't have one myself)<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=106">Bananmos</a> — Thu Oct 29, 2009 2:39 pm</p><hr />
