<title type="html"><![CDATA[More complex mappers]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5680&amp;p=51871#p51871"><![CDATA[
I would like to see a good mapper like this.  I didn't try a CPLD or FPGA before because I figured the cost/benefit had a ways to go.  Seems to be getting better though.  A 64 macrocell CPLD (with 32 I/O pins) can be had for little over $2.  That's about the price range that I'm interested in.<br /><br />If there is an inexpensive FPGA, it could be paired with an MCU for more flexible configuration options.  I suppose the same could be done with a CPLD, but they might not have enough erase/write cycles to be interesting for that (not sure).  It's just that when I think of something like this, I think the NES itself should really be able to fully use it.  It shouldn't matter as much how many crazy features the chip supports, if you can get by with only loading the parts you need at the moment.<br /><br />Yeah I remember thinking of the tile $FF trick, I didn't know at the time that MMC2/Punchout does that, so I was a little surprised.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=10">Memblers</a> — Thu Oct 29, 2009 1:09 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
