<div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Well, you'll explain me how the lack of mapper-generated IRQs would prevent you from making progress to your game.<br /></div><br />Mapper IRQs make it easier to hide vertical scrolling glitches (something I tried to solve with timed VBlank code instead), and they also would make water levels much more interesting (have you seen in Sonic games how the water level goes up and down?), for example. I also gave up on a pseudo-3D special stage because the lack of IRQs. My raycaster uses the same color for the ceiling and the floor because I don't have IRQs.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />There is several reasons keeping me to make progress on my game, mostly my low abilities when it comes to program enemies' AI and to design monsters overall, added to my own lazyness, but definitely not the lack of a cart generated IRQ.<br /></div><br />Your project was designed for simple hardware, this is a fact. There's nothing wrong with that (before you think I'm bashing your game or something), this was your choice and I'm sure you'll eventually come up with something good within the restrictions you've chosen.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />And nobody outside of nesdev communauty is going to be impressed by your graphics, no matter if you use raster effects or not...<br /></div><br />There are many other retro communities that are interested in NES releases, and they can tell when something stands out. That's enough for me.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />And I'd remember that you can generate IRQs with the DMC channels that can be combined with sprite-zero hit to trigger raster effects without wasting too much CPU time.<br /></div><br />Yeah, the might controller-corrupting DMC and the awesome solid-pixel-only sprite hit. Big help. In horizontal+vertical scrollers, meeting the hit conditions means maintaining an ugly solid tile near the place of the hit.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Using $2004 reads you could have more than 2 sync points without the need of external hardware<br /></div><br />At the expense of many sprites, meaning that less can be used for the game characters.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />but the one who release a great game using that is indirectly forcing emu authors to upgrade it so it's allright.<br /></div><br />It's hard to release a great game if you can only test it on hardware.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=95">tokumaru</a> — Thu Oct 29, 2009 8:47 am</p><hr />
