<author><name><![CDATA[Bananmos]]></name></author>
<updated>2009-10-28T12:02:48-07:00</updated>
<published>2009-10-28T12:02:48-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5680&amp;p=51829#p51829</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5680&amp;p=51829#p51829"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[More complex mappers]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5680&amp;p=51829#p51829"><![CDATA[
If you really want MMC5-like functionality and beyond, consider duplicating the Powerpak solution in mass-produced carts. Doing a search on Avnet reveals that Spartan2 chips with 15000 gates can be ordered for &lt; $10. A 50000 gate variant for &lt; $15. <br /><br />And for most kinds of prototyping your powerpak will work fine until you actually make something worthwhile. Sure it increases the costs of making the carts somewhat, but the increase is still within reasonable limits, especially if the alternative is a relatively expensive CPLD that will do much less.<br /><br />Of course, the fact that most FPGAs are RAM based (there are exceptions to this) may seem problematic. But if you use the 15K variant the FPGA configuration you need to load is only around 24KB uncompressed, and by using some extra logic parts for the reset sequence you could make the NES CPU start at a fixed 32kb bank where the consifguration data and FPGA loading code is stored.<br /><br />Sure it will be somewhat expensive to mass manufacture, but if you're already considering advanced mappers I don't think it's that critical. I don't buy the argument that this is what's stopping anybody from trying out more complicated mapper designs. I think the main reason is we tend to talk too much about ideas and play around too little with them around here... ;)<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=106">Bananmos</a> — Wed Oct 28, 2009 12:02 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
